{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"37ac9f37-2147-4757-bfdc-889319cc4323","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look in these places:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** — macOS automatically generates `.ips` or `.crash` files:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n\n2. **Console.app** — Open it and check under **Crash Reports** in the sidebar.\n\n3. **Core dumps** — These are disabled by default. To enable:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Then reproduce the crash. The core file typically appears in `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n4. **`log show`** — Check system logs for crash info:\n   ```bash\n   log show --predicate 'eventMessage contains \"your_app_name\"' --last 1h\n   ```\n\nThe **Apple crash report** (`.ips` file) is usually the quickest to find and includes the stack trace, signal info, and faulting address.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d1550ec2-8343-42aa-b7ac-334e9becb4fb","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT app on macOS when `createdump` isn't available. This is a general knowledge question — no code changes or repo exploration needed.","outputTokens":304,"requestId":"5FC7:2E8AE9:DCECED:1002ACC:69EACA68"},"id":"83a2e43b-97ea-444b-8440-182acec34b29","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:42:08.117Z","parentId":"27bfc0e2-c8fe-4439-8ff4-18c6572d089e"}
